25/* Provide forward declarations of core types which are referred to by
26 most of the compiler. This allows header files to use these types
27 (e.g. in function prototypes) without concern for whether the full
28 definitions are visible. Some other declarations that need to be
29 universally visible are here, too.
30
31 In the context of tconfig.h, most of these have special definitions
32 which prevent them from being used except in further type
33 declarations. This is a kludge; the right thing is to avoid
34 including the "tm.h" header set in the context of tconfig.h, but
35 we're not there yet. */
36
37#ifndef GCC_CORETYPES_H
38#define GCC_CORETYPES_H

157/* The thread-local storage model associated with a given VAR_DECL
158 or SYMBOL_REF. This isn't used much, but both trees and RTL refer
159 to it, so it's here. */
160enum tls_model {
161 TLS_MODEL_NONE,
162 TLS_MODEL_EMULATED,
163 TLS_MODEL_REAL,
164 TLS_MODEL_GLOBAL_DYNAMIC = TLS_MODEL_REAL,
165 TLS_MODEL_LOCAL_DYNAMIC,
166 TLS_MODEL_INITIAL_EXEC,
167 TLS_MODEL_LOCAL_EXEC
168};

195/* Callgraph node profile representation. */
196enum node_frequency {
197 /* This function most likely won't be executed at all.
198 (set only when profile feedback is available or via function attribute). */
199 NODE_FREQUENCY_UNLIKELY_EXECUTED,
200 /* For functions that are known to be executed once (i.e. constructors, destructors
201 and main function. */
202 NODE_FREQUENCY_EXECUTED_ONCE,
203 /* The default value. */
204 NODE_FREQUENCY_NORMAL,
205 /* Optimize this function hard
206 (set only when profile feedback is available or via function attribute). */
207 NODE_FREQUENCY_HOT
208};
209
210/* Ways of optimizing code. */
211enum optimization_type {
212 /* Prioritize speed over size. */
213 OPTIMIZE_FOR_SPEED,
214
215 /* Only do things that are good for both size and speed. */
216 OPTIMIZE_FOR_BOTH,
217
218 /* Prioritize size over speed. */
219 OPTIMIZE_FOR_SIZE
220};
221
222/* Possible initialization status of a variable. When requested
223 by the user, this information is tracked and recorded in the DWARF
224 debug information, along with the variable's location. */
225enum var_init_status
226{
227 VAR_INIT_STATUS_UNKNOWN,
228 VAR_INIT_STATUS_UNINITIALIZED,
229 VAR_INIT_STATUS_INITIALIZED
230};
231
232/* Names for the different levels of -Wstrict-overflow=N. The numeric
233 values here correspond to N. */
234enum warn_strict_overflow_code
235{
236 /* Overflow warning that should be issued with -Wall: a questionable
237 construct that is easy to avoid even when using macros. Example:
238 folding (x + CONSTANT > x) to 1. */
239 WARN_STRICT_OVERFLOW_ALL = 1,
240 /* Overflow warning about folding a comparison to a constant because
241 of undefined signed overflow, other than cases covered by
242 WARN_STRICT_OVERFLOW_ALL. Example: folding (abs (x) >= 0) to 1
243 (this is false when x == INT_MIN). */
244 WARN_STRICT_OVERFLOW_CONDITIONAL = 2,
245 /* Overflow warning about changes to comparisons other than folding
246 them to a constant. Example: folding (x + 1 > 1) to (x > 0). */
247 WARN_STRICT_OVERFLOW_COMPARISON = 3,
248 /* Overflow warnings not covered by the above cases. Example:
249 folding ((x * 10) / 5) to (x * 2). */
250 WARN_STRICT_OVERFLOW_MISC = 4,
251 /* Overflow warnings about reducing magnitude of constants in
252 comparison. Example: folding (x + 2 > y) to (x + 1 >= y). */
253 WARN_STRICT_OVERFLOW_MAGNITUDE = 5
254};
255
256/* The type of an alias set. Code currently assumes that variables of
257 this type can take the values 0 (the alias set which aliases
258 everything) and -1 (sometimes indicating that the alias set is
259 unknown, sometimes indicating a memory barrier) and -2 (indicating
260 that the alias set should be set to a unique value but has not been
261 set yet). */
262typedef int alias_set_type;
